      "data": {
        "content": "# Lesson 15: CoinJoin Equal-Output Heuristics\n\nThis lesson is a **heuristic walkthrough**, not cryptographic proof. You are learning to read on-chain patterns — not to assert ground truth.\n\n## What Is CoinJoin?\n\nCoinJoin is a privacy technique where multiple independent users collaborate to combine their inputs and outputs into a single Bitcoin transaction. The key insight: if several outputs share the same amount, an analyst cannot tell which output belongs to which input contributor.\n\n## Why Equal Outputs Matter\n\nWhen a transaction contains N outputs of the exact same denomination (e.g., five outputs of exactly 100,000 sats), a blockchain analyst faces N equally plausible recipients. This is the **anonymity set** — the larger it is, the more ambiguous the spend. Without coordination, naturally occurring transactions almost never produce multiple identical outputs.\n\n## The Common Input Ownership Heuristic (CIOH)\n\nThe CIOH assumes that all inputs in a transaction are controlled by the same wallet. It is one of the most powerful chain-analysis heuristics. CoinJoin directly undermines it: inputs come from different users, so the CIOH leads analysts to a false conclusion.\n\n## Common Modeling Mistakes\n\n- **Equal outputs alone are not proof.** A wallet sending dust to many addresses produces equal outputs too.\n- **Ignoring change outputs misleads.** Non-denomination outputs can provide context, but they are not a direct participant count and may include other non-denomination outputs.\n- **Real CoinJoin variants differ.** Wasabi, JoinMarket, and Whirlpool each have different coordinator policies, denomination schedules, and change patterns.\n\n## How to Read This Canvas\n\n**Lane 1 — CoinJoin Branch** (top): Enter a CSV list of output amounts. The flow detects the denomination, computes the anonymity set, counts change outputs, and calculates the equal-output ratio. Two threshold checks (anonymity >= 5, ratio >= 60%) produce a pass/fail result. A summary JSON report aggregates all metrics.\n\n**Lane 2 — Normal Baseline** (middle): Enter a normal multi-party transaction's outputs and a reference amount. The same metrics are computed so you can compare directly.\n\n**Lane 3 — Comparison** (bottom): CoinJoin metrics are compared against the normal-tx baseline. If CoinJoin scores higher on both anonymity and ratio, the comparison check passes.\n\n## Backend Path\n\nUI → POST /bulk_calculate → graph_logic (topological sort + param extraction) → calc_func.py (coinjoin_* helpers) → JSON results back to nodes.",
        "fontSize": 20,
        "width": 1100,
        "height": 860,
        "title": "Text Info Node",
        "dirty": false
      },
      "width": 1120,
      "height": 880
    },
    {
      "id": "node_compare_lane_notes",
      "type": "shadcnTextInfo",
      "position": {
        "x": 1450,
        "y": 2860
      },
      "data": {
        "content": "## Compare Lane — What to Look For\n\n**CoinJoin Anon > Normal**: If CoinJoin's equal-output count exceeds the normal transaction's equal-output count for the same reference amount, it demonstrates the meaningful ambiguity gain from coordination.\n\n**CoinJoin Ratio > Normal**: If the equal-output ratio (equal outputs / total outputs) is significantly higher in the CoinJoin lane, the transaction structure is more uniform — a strong heuristic signal.\n\nBoth comparisons together feed the final `check_result` node. **TRUE** means the CoinJoin pattern dominates the baseline on both measures.\n\n**Note on thresholds**: The threshold nodes in the CoinJoin lane (anonymity >= 5, ratio >= 60%) are industry-typical starting points used by tools like OXT and BlockSci. They are not consensus rules — analysts tune them per context.",
        "fontSize": 18,
        "width": 620,
        "height": 480,
        "title": "Text Info Node",
        "dirty": false
      },
      "width": 640,
      "height": 500
